286
00:20:57,800 --> 00:21:00,990
I'm sorry if we appeared to act a little hastily.

287
00:21:01,080 --> 00:21:03,030
Anyway, I'm very pleased.

288
00:21:03,120 --> 00:21:05,260
I feel like Jack and the Beanstalk, 

289
00:21:05,260 --> 00:21:07,110
stealing the treasure from the giant's castle.

290
00:21:07,200 --> 00:21:09,790
-What?
-Nothing.

291
00:21:09,880 --> 00:21:11,910
-Nice motorcar!
-Not mine, I'm afraid.

292
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:14,090
Borrowed it from a chum in the RAF. 

293
00:21:14,090 --> 00:21:14,750
I can't afford one.

294
00:21:14,840 --> 00:21:18,030
-Of course.
-Are you all right? Thank you so much.

295
00:21:18,120 --> 00:21:21,990
Look, if there are any expenses involved, tools or whatever,

296
00:21:22,080 --> 00:21:24,110
make a note of them and send them to me.

297
00:21:24,200 --> 00:21:26,150
Thank you so much.

298
00:21:38,840 --> 00:21:41,710
News of your achievement is all over town,

299
00:21:42,520 --> 00:21:47,110
as is the fact that you are about to win 20,000 pounds.

300
00:21:48,080 --> 00:21:51,230
You're going to be a very popular young man, Mr Harrison.

301
00:21:51,320 --> 00:21:53,270
-I envy you.
-Thank you.

302
00:21:53,360 --> 00:21:56,350
But I have to get back to London before I can be sure.

303
00:21:57,680 --> 00:21:59,630
Mr Harrison...

304
00:22:00,600 --> 00:22:04,470
You are clearly not aware that while you were at sea,

305
00:22:04,560 --> 00:22:06,510
war was declared with Spain.

306
00:22:06,510 --> 00:22:07,450
Frankly, 

307
00:22:07,450 --> 00:22:11,030
I'm surprised the admiralty permitted you to travel to Jamaica at all.

308
00:22:11,840 --> 00:22:15,510
They must have known that you were likely to be stranded here.

309
00:22:15,600 --> 00:22:17,950
Well, there has to be a ship going back to England.

310
00:22:18,040 --> 00:22:20,230
No. I'm afraid not.

311
00:22:20,320 --> 00:22:23,550
Besides, it would be too dangerous to travel unescorted.

312
00:22:23,640 --> 00:22:27,670
I'm sure you wouldn't wish your watch to be captured by the Spanish.

313
00:22:29,560 --> 00:22:31,790
Enjoy yourself.

314
00:22:33,120 --> 00:22:35,070
This is a very beautiful island.

315
00:22:38,720 --> 00:22:42,310
-Where are you going to put it?
-In the attic.

316
00:22:43,160 --> 00:22:45,110
And the job?

317
00:22:45,200 --> 00:22:46,950
What?

318
00:22:47,040 --> 00:22:49,470
You said you were going to London about a job.

319
00:22:50,480 --> 00:22:52,430
Oh, yes, I did.

320
00:22:52,520 --> 00:22:55,080
-I met Uncle Mac.
-Uncle Mac?

321
00:22:55,160 --> 00:22:57,110
You don't have an Uncle Mac!

322
00:22:57,840 --> 00:23:01,190
I do now. He offered me a job on the wireless.

323
00:23:02,080 --> 00:23:04,110
You're not going to play records, are you?

324
00:23:04,200 --> 00:23:06,150
Not quite.

325
00:23:30,440 --> 00:23:32,150
Do you speak English?

326
00:23:32,240 --> 00:23:34,990
She wants to know which of you is the rich bastard.

327
00:23:39,640 --> 00:23:42,470
My dear girl, I'm the rich bastard.

328
00:23:43,360 --> 00:23:46,430
Perhaps you would allow me the honour of the next dance.

329
00:23:56,920 --> 00:23:58,270
Look over there.

330
00:23:59,560 --> 00:24:02,430
-Who are they?
-They're from the Merlin.

331
00:24:02,520 --> 00:24:06,750
Arrived this afternoon to offload some prisoners and claim their bounty.

332
00:24:06,840 --> 00:24:09,720
The ship's a hulk, two masts sprung, 

333
00:24:09,720 --> 00:24:10,910
and half the rigging gone.

334
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:14,390
They were on their way to England when they came across a privateer.

335
00:24:14,480 --> 00:24:16,230
Lucky bastards.

336
00:24:16,320 --> 00:24:18,270
What's the name of the captain?

337
00:24:18,360 --> 00:24:20,310
Irish fellow. Bourke.

338
00:24:20,400 --> 00:24:21,950
William Bourke

339
00:24:28,040 --> 00:24:30,550
Let's see... two,

340
00:24:30,640 --> 00:24:32,870
four, six,

341
00:24:32,960 --> 00:24:34,910
8 10 12\Neight, ten, twelve.

342
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:37,270
So, that's three officers and twelve men,

343
00:24:41,240 --> 00:24:45,390
Harrison, we'll take you with us as long as you're ready to leave tomorrow.

344
00:24:46,600 --> 00:24:48,550
Tomorrow?

345
00:24:48,640 --> 00:24:50,590
We sail on the noontide.

346
00:24:51,280 --> 00:24:53,070
-Mr Sayer!
-Sir?

347
00:24:53,760 --> 00:24:56,670
-I need you finished up there within the hour.
-We'll be ready.

348
00:24:56,760 --> 00:24:59,910
I'll have to check to establish the longitude of the island.

349
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:01,950
Can't you wait another day?

350
00:25:02,040 --> 00:25:05,030
My orders say I must make sail as soon as I'm seaworthy.

351
00:25:06,720 --> 00:25:10,230
So... you'd better get on with it, then.

352
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:26,950
-How is it?
-Almost there.

353
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:29,950
What time do you make it?

354
00:25:30,040 --> 00:25:32,310
-Well, the watch says...
-Not the watch.

355
00:25:32,400 --> 00:25:34,430
I don't need the time back in England.

356
00:25:34,520 --> 00:25:36,470
The Merlin leaves on the noontide.

357
00:25:36,560 --> 00:25:39,310
-How long have I got?
-About an hour, I should say.

358
00:25:40,280 --> 00:25:42,190
I'll do the calculations later. 

359
00:25:42,190 --> 00:25:44,750
I don't want to be stranded here for four months.

360
00:25:44,840 --> 00:25:48,150
Maskelyne may be on his way back from St Helena with his lunar results.

361
00:25:49,240 --> 00:25:51,190
Come on. Give us a hand.

362
00:25:54,960 --> 00:25:58,500
William, one of these chaps says he's a fisherman.

363
00:25:58,600 --> 00:26:00,300
He's got a boat moored on the beach below. 

364
00:26:00,300 --> 00:26:02,300
He could take you out. It would save time.

365
00:26:02,400 --> 00:26:05,070
-Are you sure?
-I don't think you have an option.

366
00:26:05,160 --> 00:26:08,110
-The Merlin won't wait for you.
-Well, come on, then!

367
00:26:38,120 --> 00:26:40,270
-Good luck!
-Thank you!

368
00:26:58,120 --> 00:27:01,390
Mr Harrison, I can see you live dangerously.

369
00:27:01,480 --> 00:27:04,630
-I like that. Welcome aboard.
-Thank you, Captain.

370
00:27:06,240 --> 00:27:08,470
I can see I'm not the only one.

371
00:27:09,360 --> 00:27:12,230
-Set the upper topsails, Mr Parker.
-Aye, Captain.

372
00:27:12,320 --> 00:27:16,830
-Set the upper topsails!
-Set the upper topsails!

373
00:27:27,840 --> 00:27:31,270
Have done with your sums, Mr Harrison. Go up on deck.

374
00:27:32,160 --> 00:27:34,110
It's a fine sight.

375
00:27:34,200 --> 00:27:36,760
I cannot be certain till we are back in England,

376
00:27:36,840 --> 00:27:38,790
but, according to my workings,

377
00:27:38,880 --> 00:27:40,830
if we take the rate into account,

378
00:27:40,920 --> 00:27:42,720
we've lost under a minute 

379
00:27:42,720 --> 00:27:44,670
since the watch left London ten weeks ago.

380
00:27:44,760 --> 00:27:46,710
The er... rate?

381
00:27:47,920 --> 00:27:50,480
Well, we know the watch loses 211/22 seconds a day.

382
00:27:50,560 --> 00:27:51,800
We call that the going rate. 

383
00:27:51,800 --> 00:27:54,430
I used that in my calculations for Madeira.

384
00:27:54,520 --> 00:27:56,930
Taking that into account, 

385
00:27:56,930 --> 00:28:00,550
there's a possible error in longitude of less than half a degree.

386
00:28:00,640 --> 00:28:02,990
Let me be the first to congratulate you.

387
00:28:03,080 --> 00:28:04,830
No, thank you.

388
00:28:04,920 --> 00:28:06,710
I'm already drunk.

389
00:28:06,800 --> 00:28:10,630
All my life... my father's life,

390
00:28:11,480 --> 00:28:13,670
has been for this moment.

391
00:28:18,600 --> 00:28:20,550
Listen.

392
00:28:20,640 --> 00:28:22,830
If the watch stops now, sir,

393
00:28:24,040 --> 00:28:25,990
so does my heart,

394
00:28:26,080 --> 00:28:28,540
for there will be no proof of its achievement.

395
00:28:30,040 --> 00:28:31,990
Half a degree.

396
00:28:32,080 --> 00:28:34,230
We've won the prize, Captain.

397
00:28:34,320 --> 00:28:36,270
We've won the prize!

398
00:28:39,800 --> 00:28:41,790
Captain, Spaniard about a cannon shot away.

399
00:28:41,880 --> 00:28:43,520
Every man to his station! 

400
00:28:43,520 --> 00:28:45,830
Tell the master gunner to report to me on deck.

401
00:28:49,400 --> 00:28:52,830
Aft, loosen your guns! Get those portholes open!

402
00:28:55,800 --> 00:28:57,750
I don't know what she's waiting for.

403
00:29:02,560 --> 00:29:04,860
-Stand the guns by. -Aye, Captain.

404
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:07,950
Steady!

405
00:29:11,120 --> 00:29:14,230
-Fire as she comes by!
-Fire as she comes by!

406
00:29:31,520 --> 00:29:35,190
The dial is of white enamel with an ornamental design in black.

407
00:29:35,280 --> 00:29:38,570
The hour and minute hands are of blued steel, 

408
00:29:38,570 --> 00:29:40,630
and there is a polished centre second hand.

409
00:29:41,800 --> 00:29:45,750
The movement can be swung out of the case, turning on a bolt and joint,

410
00:29:45,840 --> 00:29:48,870
exactly as do those of ordinary watches of the period.

411
00:29:53,760 --> 00:29:57,430
It's no good. We're going to have to try and outrun her.

412
00:29:57,520 --> 00:29:59,470
Mr Markland,

413
00:29:59,560 --> 00:30:02,790
put on all the sail she can carry and set a course due east.

414
00:30:02,880 --> 00:30:05,030
Aye aye, Captain.

415
00:30:05,120 --> 00:30:07,110
Can we get any more men aloft, Mr Bandelwine?

416
00:30:07,200 --> 00:30:09,150
We're taking on water forward.

417
00:30:09,240 --> 00:30:12,690
We've got to keep the pumps manned, sir.

418
00:30:15,120 --> 00:30:18,740
I want eight men at the pumps at all times, changing every quarter.

419
00:30:18,840 --> 00:30:22,750
-Mr Hallam, I'm holding you responsible.
-Yes, sir.

420
00:30:40,400 --> 00:30:45,260
The pallet radius and crown wheel are both very small compared with the balance,

421
00:30:46,320 --> 00:30:48,270
but, not content with this,

422
00:30:48,360 --> 00:30:51,430
Harrison fitted, between the fourth and crown wheels,

423
00:30:51,520 --> 00:30:53,690
a most ingenious remontoir,

424
00:30:53,690 --> 00:30:58,190
whose action, at first sight, is almost uncanny.

425
00:31:08,080 --> 00:31:10,640
Right, lads, over she goes!

426
00:31:19,040 --> 00:31:21,340
Steady up now. Take it up. Take it up there.

427
00:31:24,320 --> 00:31:25,430
Boatswain?

428
00:31:25,520 --> 00:31:26,850
If we get it on top of the hole, 

429
00:31:26,850 --> 00:31:28,080
the suction should hold it.

430
00:31:28,160 --> 00:31:30,750
We'll have to keep the pumps going day and night, sir.

431
00:31:30,840 --> 00:31:32,790
The mist is starting to lift.

432
00:31:33,760 --> 00:31:35,370
Quick as you can, Boatswain.  

433
00:31:35,370 --> 00:31:37,110
You heard the captain. Steady now.

434
00:31:37,200 --> 00:31:39,150
Haul away! Come on, now!

435
00:31:39,880 --> 00:31:42,150
The watch beats five to a second,

436
00:31:42,240 --> 00:31:44,870
a slight recoil being perceptible at each beat,

437
00:31:45,880 --> 00:31:48,310
and goes for 30 hours.

438
00:31:48,400 --> 00:31:51,270
The plates are of brass, polished, but not gilt.

439
00:31:52,360 --> 00:31:54,990
The pivot holes are jewelled as far as the third wheel,

440
00:31:55,080 --> 00:31:58,150
that is to say, those of the balance, staff, detent,

441
00:31:58,240 --> 00:32:02,150
contrate wheel, fly, fifth, fourth and third wheels.

442
00:32:02,240 --> 00:32:04,190
The jewels are rubies,

443
00:32:04,280 --> 00:32:06,230
and the end stones, diamonds.

444
00:32:06,320 --> 00:32:08,270
It is a masterpiece,

445
00:32:08,360 --> 00:32:11,550
weighing only slightly less than the brain that conceived it.

446
00:32:13,360 --> 00:32:15,310
Harrison.

447
00:32:19,480 --> 00:32:21,430
Morning, Captain.

448
00:32:22,360 --> 00:32:24,310
How is your watch?

449
00:32:25,200 --> 00:32:27,150
Dry, sir, I think.

450
00:32:27,240 --> 00:32:29,540
It must be the only thing on board the ship that is.

451
00:32:29,640 --> 00:32:32,670
Who will believe in a naval watch that cannot survive a storm?

452
00:32:32,760 --> 00:32:35,830
There's many a ship that doesn't survive a storm, Mr Harrison,

453
00:32:35,920 --> 00:32:37,870
but the navy don't stop making them.

454
00:32:37,960 --> 00:32:41,830
It's not the navy I have to convince, sir. It is the Board of Longitude.

455
00:32:48,440 --> 00:32:52,830
I'm very sorry, Reverend, to hear that your journey to St Helena was unsuccessful.

456
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:57,230
Unsuccessful, sir? I think you've been misinformed.

457
00:32:57,320 --> 00:33:01,470
1,000 miles to observe the planet Venus, and it turns out to be a cloudy day.

458
00:33:02,560 --> 00:33:04,510
Am I misinformed?

459
00:33:04,600 --> 00:33:07,550
The transit of Venus was but one part of my expedition.

460
00:33:07,640 --> 00:33:10,270
My lunar observations on board were most interesting,

461
00:33:10,360 --> 00:33:12,310
as I shall explain to the Board.

462
00:33:13,800 --> 00:33:15,750
Mr Harrison.

463
00:33:18,160 --> 00:33:20,590
-Mr William Harrison.
-We'll go together.

464
00:33:20,680 --> 00:33:22,750
My instructions are quite clear, sir.

465
00:33:22,840 --> 00:33:26,030
Don't worry, they can't hurt us. We've won.

466
00:33:43,680 --> 00:33:48,030
Mr Harrison, is this your idea of a scientific observation?

467
00:33:48,120 --> 00:33:49,690
I must apologise, sir, 

468
00:33:49,690 --> 00:33:51,890
but the journey back was very difficult, 

469
00:33:51,900 --> 00:33:53,570
and the papers were damaged.

470
00:33:53,600 --> 00:33:55,070
I am referring to the fact that 

471
00:33:55,070 --> 00:33:57,870
it appears only one observation was taken in Jamaica.

472
00:33:57,960 --> 00:33:59,510
No, no. Two, sir.

473
00:33:59,600 --> 00:34:03,140
But the second, it appears, was taken from another position.

474
00:34:03,240 --> 00:34:04,770
I had very little time, sir, 

475
00:34:04,770 --> 00:34:06,020
but I can assure you 

476
00:34:06,020 --> 00:34:08,260
the observation was most carefully taken,

477
00:34:08,360 --> 00:34:11,310
with witnesses present, as instructed by the Board.

478
00:34:14,680 --> 00:34:18,030
Mr Harrison, do you have any formal astronomical training?

479
00:34:18,200 --> 00:34:19,260
No, sir, 

480
00:34:19,260 --> 00:34:22,990
but I have been taking observations for my father since I was six years old.

481
00:34:23,080 --> 00:34:25,190
Really?

482
00:34:36,240 --> 00:34:38,190
Mr John Harrison.

483
00:34:55,280 --> 00:34:59,750
My lords, gentlemen, if I may beg your indulgence,

484
00:34:59,840 --> 00:35:03,000
it is 25 years since I first had the honour 

485
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:04,830
to address this Board

486
00:35:05,200 --> 00:35:08,310
under the chairmanship of Dr Edmund Halley,

487
00:35:08,690 --> 00:35:12,200
and since that time I worked with only one ambition to

488
00:35:12,200 --> 00:35:16,790
to satisfy your requirements, as laid down by act of parliament 

489
00:35:16,880 --> 00:35:18,950
for the discovery of longitude at sea.

490
00:35:19,960 --> 00:35:22,790
It is with both great pride and honour

491
00:35:23,960 --> 00:35:27,740
and humility that I stand here today with my son

492
00:35:27,840 --> 00:35:29,790
after his great trial.

493
00:35:29,880 --> 00:35:31,830
Thank you, Mr Harrison.

494
00:35:31,920 --> 00:35:33,870
-May I?
-Thank you.

495
00:35:36,960 --> 00:35:40,580
I have asked you here to inform you of the resolution of the Board,

496
00:35:40,680 --> 00:35:45,700
that firstly, the brief calculations of Mr William Harrison are to be sent for computation

497
00:35:45,800 --> 00:35:51,150
and the instruments used in those observations are also to be sent for examination.

498
00:35:51,240 --> 00:35:54,310
The Board will then consider these reports at a further meeting,

499
00:35:54,400 --> 00:35:58,750
the date of which will be announced in due course.

500
00:35:58,840 --> 00:36:01,950
That will be all for now, gentlemen.

501
00:36:14,200 --> 00:36:16,150
Sir, I am an old man,

502
00:36:16,240 --> 00:36:20,590
and an old man can sometimes find his senses unexpectedly weakened.

503
00:36:20,680 --> 00:36:25,590
There is, perhaps, an element of your argument that I have misunderstood,

504
00:36:25,680 --> 00:36:27,630
or even misheard.

505
00:36:28,640 --> 00:36:30,590
My watch...

506
00:36:30,900 --> 00:36:38,150
Lost one minute, 53 and half seconds after 81 days at sea,

507
00:36:38,840 --> 00:36:41,870
as witnesses signed in the papers you have before you,

508
00:36:41,960 --> 00:36:44,390
